1.2 Implement The 1D GD Algorithm¶

2. Implementation of 1D GD Algorithm¶

In [494]:
## Function
def f1D(x):
    r = x**2
    return r

## Gradient function
def gradientf1D(x):
    r = 2*x
    return r
In [495]:
## function to implement 1D gradient function
def implement_gradient(cur_x, stopping_criterion_e, iters, max_iters, rate):
    while np.linalg.norm(gradientf1D(cur_x)) > stopping_criterion_e and iters < max_iters:
        prev_x = cur_x #Store current x value in prev_x
        cur_x = cur_x - rate * gradientf1D(prev_x) #Grad descent
        iters = iters + 1 #iteration count
        print("Iteration", iters, "\nX value is ", prev_x, "\nf(x) value is ", f1D(prev_x), 
              "\nGradient value is ", gradientf1D(prev_x))
    print("The solution is ", prev_x, " and it took ", iters, " iterations")
In [496]:
cur_x = 1 ##Starting value of x
stopping_criterion_e = 0.01 ##This tells us when to stop the algorithm
iters = 0 #Initial number of iterations
max_iters = 1000 ##Maximum number of iterations
rate = 0.1  ##Learning rate

implement_gradient(cur_x, stopping_criterion_e, iters, max_iters, rate)

The solution is  0.000505499848289726  and it took  411  iterations

From the above experiments, we could see that smaller the learning rate, it takes many iterations to reach the minimum point which is obvious. Also, we could see that the start point(initial value) also affects the number of iterations. In our above case, the location minimum point is at 0.0009 approximately 0. Hence starting at 1 makes it with less iterations and 2 as starting point takes a little more iterations.

1.3 Implement The 2D Version¶

1. What's the location of the true minimum of f(x)?
The location of true minimum changes with different start value, though its approximately [0,0].

In [501]:
## This function can be used to check the true minimum
#optimize.minimize(f2D, [2, -3], method="CG") #--Parameters to be passed: function name, start value
In [502]:
x = np.array([[2], [-3]])
A = np.array([[1,0],[0,1]])

print("The eigen values are ", np.linalg.eig(A)[0])

The eigen values are  [ 1.  1.]
In [503]:
## Function
def f2D(x):
    r = x.T @ A @ x
    return r


## Gradient function
def gradientf2D(x):
    r = 2 * A @ x
    return r

x = np.array([[2], [-3]])

gradientf2D(x)
Out[503]:
array([[ 4],
       [-6]])

1.3.5 Implementation of 2D GD algorithm¶

In [504]:
cur_x = np.array([[2], [-3]]) ##Starting value of x
stopping_criterion_e = 0.01 ##This tells us when to stop the algorithm
iters = 0 #Initial number of iterations
max_iters = 1000 ##Maximum number of iterations
rate = 0.01  ##Learning rate


## function to implement 2D gradient function
def implement_gradient_2D(cur_x, iters, max_iters, rate):
    while np.linalg.norm(gradientf2D(cur_x)) > stopping_criterion_e and iters < max_iters:
        print("Norm val is ", np.linalg.norm(gradientf2D(cur_x)))
        prev_x = cur_x #Store current x value in prev_x
        cur_x = cur_x - rate * gradientf2D(prev_x) #Grad descent
        iters = iters + 1 #iteration count
        print("Iteration", iters, "\nX value is ", prev_x, "\nf(x) value is ", f2D(prev_x), "\nGradient value is ", gradientf2D(prev_x))
    print("The solution is ", prev_x, " and it took ", iters, " iterations") 
    
    
implement_gradient_2D(cur_x, iters, max_iters, rate)

1.3.6 Visualize the 2D plot¶

In [505]:
def plot_graph(startpt, nsteps, lrate):
    x1range = [-3,3]
    x2range = [-3,3]

    ex1 = np.linspace(x1range[0], x1range[1], 30)
    ex2 = np.linspace(x2range[0], x2range[1], 30)
    (xm1, xm2) = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    x1 = xm1.ravel()
    x2 = xm2.ravel()
    z = np.empty_like(xm1)
    for i in range(30):
        for j in range(30):
            x = np.array((xm1[i,j], xm2[i,j]))
            z[i,j] = f2D(x)

    fig = plt.figure(figsize = [10,10])
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax.set_aspect('equal')  # ensure equal aspect ratio
    cs = ax.contour(ex1, ex2, z) # make contour plot
    ax.clabel(cs, inline=1)  # add contour values
    
    # starting point
    a0 = startpt[0]; a1 = startpt[1]
    ax.plot(a0,a1, 'o')
    #print(a0,a1)
    
    # do the gradient descent loop and plot the progress
    for i in range(nsteps):
        a0old, a1old = a0, a1
        startpt = np.matrix(startpt).reshape(2,1) - lrate * gradientf2D(np.matrix(startpt).reshape(2,1))
        a0 = startpt.item(0); a1 = startpt.item(0)
        #print(a0, a1) # the updated parameters
        ax.plot(a0,a1,'o')
        ax.plot([a0old,a0],[a1old,a1], '-') # connect the dots
        
    plt.show()
In [506]:
x = np.array([[2], [-3]])
A = np.array([[1,0],[0,1]])
plot_graph([2,-3], 50, 0.01) #Arguments passed startpt, nsteps(no of points to be shown), learningrate

From the above plot, we could see that the starting point is (2,-3) marked by the green line. The learning rate is set to 0.01. As we progress we could see that the point converges towards the center of the circles(location minimum). As we have stopped after 50 steps, the graph reached closer to the minimum point.

1.3.8 Implementation of 5D algorithm¶

In [509]:
A = np.arange(25).reshape(5,5) + 1
I = np.identity(5)

A = 0.5 * (A + A.T) + 10 * I
x = np.array([[10], [20], [30], [40], [50]])

iters = 0
max_iters = 1000
rate = 0.01
implement_gradient_2D(x, iters, max_iters, rate)

The solution is  [[-0.00502007]

 [-0.00087244]
 [ 0.00120137]
 [ 0.00327518]]  and it took  1000  iterations

The learning rates have been set as 0.001, 0.005 and 0.01 for the 5D algorithms as higher learning rate results in very huge norm values. Similar to the other cases(1D and 2D), higher the learning rate, faster the convergence.

When we compare the 1D, 2D and 5D cases, higher dimensions take more steps to converge even if the learning rates are same. In our example, for 1D algorithm the convergence is as follows for different learning rates - 0.01: 297 iters, 0.05: 57 iters, 0.1: 27 iters. On the other hand for 2D algorithm the learning rate and convergence iterations are, 0.01: 326 iters, 0.05: 63 iters, 0.1: 30 iters. Thus 2D algorithm has taken more iterations to converge.

It is interesting to see that in 5D case, the convergence is achieved after 118 iterations for learning rate 0.01 and 240 iterations for learning rate 0.005.

1.4 Condition Numbers¶

9. Show, on computer, that it is singular! Show it without error messages but using relevant linear algebra functions/properties instead.¶

In [512]:
#Creating a singular matrix
singular_matrix = np.ones((2,2))

print("The eigen values of this matrix are ", np.linalg.eig(singular_matrix)[0])

#Identity matrix
I2 = np.identity(2)
A = np.array([[1,0],[0,1]])

The eigen values of this matrix are  [ 2.  0.]

As one of the eigen values is 0, we can know that it is a singular matrix!!

In [513]:
def test_matrix_convergence(iters, max_iters, rate, alpha, startpt):
    #Make it non-singular by adding alpha amount of identity matrix to it
    non_singular_matrix = singular_matrix + alpha * I2 
    print("The non-singular matrix is \n", non_singular_matrix)
    print("The eigen values of this matrix are ", np.linalg.eig(non_singular_matrix)[0])
    print("The condition number of this matrix is ", np.linalg.cond(non_singular_matrix))
    print("The learning rate is ", rate, " and ", "stopping criteria set as ", max_iters, " iterations")
    implement_gradient_2D(non_singular_matrix, iters, max_iters, rate) 
    plot_graph(startpt, max_iters//10, rate)

From the above plots, we could see that higher the condition number, faster the convergence. Also, we could note that decreasing the alpha value, increases the condition number. In above case, when the alpha was set as 100, the condition number is 1.02 and it took 508 iterations to converge. Similarly, when the alpha value was set to 1 and 0.01, the condition number is 3 and 201 and it took 320, 297 iterations to converge respectively.

1.5 Loss function of linear regression¶

In [517]:
seed(1)
X_random = np.reshape(np.random.random(100), (100,1))
interceptCol = np.ones((X_random.shape[0],1))

# Add an intercept column to the model.
X = np.abs(np.concatenate((interceptCol, X_random), axis=1))

# The noise column
disturbanceVector = np.random.normal(0,1,100)

# Beta
betaval = np.array([1,1])


# Calculate the mean square error - loss function
def f_sse(beta):
    # Y vector with noise
    y_true = np.matmul(X, betaval) + disturbanceVector
    # Actual Y vector
    y_pred = np.matmul(X, beta)
    return np.mean((y_pred - y_true)**2)

print("The loss is ", f_sse(beta))

#L(x) = e'e = (y-X(beta))' (y-X(beta))

def gradient_sse(beta):
    # Y vector with noise
    y_true = np.matmul(X, betaval) + disturbanceVector
    # Actual Y vector
    y_pred = np.matmul(X, beta)
    b_gradient = -(2) * np.mean(y_pred - y_true)   ## 2X'(y-X(beta))
    return b_gradient

gradient_sse(betaval)

The loss is  1.19060727906
Out[517]:
0.043531938919114568
In [518]:
cur_x = betaval #np.array([[2], [-3]]) ##Starting value of x
iters = 0 #Initial number of iterations
max_iters = 100 ##Maximum number of iterations
rate = 0.01  ##Learning rate


## function to implement 2D gradient function
def implement_gradient_sse(cur_x, iters, max_iters, rate):
    while iters < max_iters:
        prev_x = cur_x #Store current x value in prev_x
        cur_x = cur_x - rate * gradient_sse(prev_x) #Grad descent
        iters = iters + 1 #iteration count
        print("Iteration", iters, "\nX value is ", prev_x, "\nf(x) a.k.a loss value is ", f_sse(prev_x), 
              "\nGradient value is ", gradient_sse(prev_x))
    print("The solution is ", prev_x, " and it took ", iters, " iterations") 

    
implement_gradient_sse(cur_x, iters, max_iters, rate)

In [521]:
def plot_graph_sse(startpt, nsteps, lrate):
    x1range = [-30,30]
    x2range = [-30,30]

    ex1 = np.linspace(x1range[0], x1range[1], 30)
    ex2 = np.linspace(x2range[0], x2range[1], 30)
    (xm1, xm2) = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    x1 = xm1.ravel()
    x2 = xm2.ravel()
    z = np.empty_like(xm1)
    for i in range(30):
        for j in range(30):
            x = np.array((xm1[i,j], xm2[i,j]))
            z[i,j] = f_sse(x)

    fig = plt.figure(figsize = [10,10])
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax.set_aspect('equal')  # ensure equal aspect ratio
    cs = ax.contour(ex1, ex2, z) # make contour plot
    ax.clabel(cs, inline=1)  # add contour values
    
    # starting point
    a0 = startpt[0]; a1 = startpt[1]
    ax.plot(a0,a1, 'o')
    
    # do the gradient descent loop and plot the progress
    for i in range(nsteps):
        a0old, a1old = a0, a1
        startpt = np.matrix(startpt).reshape(2,1) - lrate * gradient_sse(np.matrix(startpt).reshape(2,1))
        a0 = startpt.item(0); a1 = startpt.item(0)
        ax.plot(a0,a1,'o')
        ax.plot([a0old,a0],[a1old,a1], '-') # connect the dots
        
    plt.show()

plot_graph_sse([1,1], 10, 0.2)

In the above plots we can see that, increasing the learning rates makes the convergence faster. But after a particular learning rate, the convergence moves in the opposite direction. Hence we would stop with the learning rate from which we reached the minimum point

1.6 Extra Challenge¶

In [524]:
## function to implement 1D gradient function
def implement_gradient_lr(cur_x, stopping_criterion_e, iters, max_iters, rate):
    while np.linalg.norm(gradientf1D(cur_x)) > stopping_criterion_e and iters < max_iters:
        prev_x = cur_x #Store current x value in prev_x
        cur_x = cur_x - rate * gradientf1D(prev_x) #Grad descent
        iters = iters + 1 #iteration count
        if(cur_x - prev_x) < 0:  ##If move towards minimum increase the learning rate by 10%
            rate += rate * 0.1
        else: #Else decrease it by 25%
            rate = rate/4
        print("Iteration", iters, "\nX value is ", prev_x, "\nf(x) value is ", f1D(prev_x), "\nGradient value is ", gradientf1D(prev_x))
    print("The solution is ", prev_x, " and it took ", iters, " iterations") 
    
    
#Change the starting value to 2, initial learning rate as 0.1
implement_gradient_lr(2, 0.01, 0, 1000, 0.1)

The adaptive learning rate does magic to the convergence. I tried implementing adaptive learning rate for 1D case. Doing that reduced the number of iterations to converge drastically. Without the adaptive algorithm, for learning rate 0.1 and 0.01, the number of iterations were 27 and 297 respectively. But with the adaptive algorithm, the iterations reduced to 13 and 35 for learning rates 0.1 and 0.01 respectively
